Description: CVE-2026-3833 - Case-insensitive DNS/email label comparison in name constraints
 GnuTLS compared nameConstraints labels case-sensitively, allowing SAN
 casing tricks to bypass excluded/permitted subtree checks (RFC 5280
 7.2). Upstream 3.8.13 adds case-insensitive comparison in the name
 constraint comparator path.
 .
 Debian's gnutls28 package applies extensive debian/patches refactors to
 lib/x509/name_constraints.c (rich comparators). This change follows
 upstream commit 19f6508647bdcd3ce21130201e484d7ca6d962c5 for that layout:
 add compare_strings_case_insensitive() using c_strncasecmp and use it
 for per-label DNS comparisons inside compare_dns_names() (covering
 rfc822Name domains via compare_emails()).
Origin: upstream, https://gitlab.com/gnutls/gnutls/-/commit/19f6508647bdcd3ce21130201e484d7ca6d962c5
Bug-Debian: https://bugs.debian.org/1135319
Author: Alexander Sosedkin <asosedkin@redhat.com>
Last-Update: 2026-05-15

--- a/lib/x509/name_constraints.c
+++ b/lib/x509/name_constraints.c
@@ -34,6 +34,7 @@
 #include "x509_b64.h"
 #include "x509_int.h"
 #include "x509_ext_int.h"
+#include "c-strcase.h"
 #include <libtasn1.h>
 
 #include "ip.h"
@@ -80,7 +81,7 @@
 	NC_SORTS_AFTER = 2 /* unrelated constraints */
 };
 
-/* A helper to compare just a pair of strings with this rich comparison */
+/* Helpers to compare just a pair of strings with this rich comparison */
 static enum name_constraint_relation
 compare_strings(const void *n1, size_t n1_len, const void *n2, size_t n2_len)
 {
@@ -96,6 +97,22 @@
 	return NC_EQUAL;
 }
 
+static enum name_constraint_relation
+compare_strings_case_insensitive(const void *n1, size_t n1_len, const void *n2,
+				 size_t n2_len)
+{
+	int r = c_strncasecmp(n1, n2, MIN(n1_len, n2_len));
+	if (r < 0)
+		return NC_SORTS_BEFORE;
+	if (r > 0)
+		return NC_SORTS_AFTER;
+	if (n1_len < n2_len)
+		return NC_SORTS_BEFORE;
+	if (n1_len > n2_len)
+		return NC_SORTS_AFTER;
+	return NC_EQUAL;
+}
+
 /* Rich-compare DNS names. Example order/relationships:
  * z.x.a INCLUDED_BY x.a BEFORE y.a INCLUDED_BY a BEFORE x.b BEFORE y.b */
 static enum name_constraint_relation compare_dns_names(const gnutls_datum_t *n1,
@@ -121,8 +138,9 @@
 		while (j && n2->data[j - 1] != '.')
 			j--;
 
-		rel = compare_strings(&n1->data[i], i_end - i, &n2->data[j],
-				      j_end - j);
+		rel = compare_strings_case_insensitive(&n1->data[i], i_end - i,
+						&n2->data[j],
+						j_end - j);
 		if (rel == NC_SORTS_BEFORE) /* x.a BEFORE y.a */
 			return NC_SORTS_BEFORE;
 		if (rel == NC_SORTS_AFTER) /* y.a AFTER x.a */
Description: CVE-2026-33846 - Fix DTLS reassembly heap buffer overflow
 Heap buffer overflow in GnuTLS DTLS handshake fragment reassembly.
 The merge_handshake_packet() function matches and merges incoming
 handshake fragments based solely on handshake type, without validating
 that the message_length field remains consistent across all fragments
 or checking the sequence number. Attackers can send crafted fragments
 with conflicting length values, triggering allocation of smaller buffers
 followed by out-of-bounds writes.
 .
 This patch adds sequence number matching to DTLS fragment reassembly
 and introduces boundary validation checks to prevent heap overwrites.
Origin: upstream, https://gitlab.com/gnutls/gnutls/-/commit/092c65d004e2f125f2fea3db84d801ac49a09f78
Bug: https://gitlab.com/gnutls/gnutls/-/issues/1816
Author: GnuTLS developers
Last-Update: 2026-05-06

